      "text": "### Value Functions\n\n* **Firms:**\n\t* *Value of posting:*$$\\begin{equation*}\n    V(h, x) = - \\kappa + q(\\theta(h,x))\\int J(\\psi, h, x) dF(\\psi)\n    \\end{equation*}$$\n    \n\t - *Value of an ongoing match:*$$\\begin{equation*}\n    J(\\psi, h, x) = Y(\\alpha^*(\\psi, h)\\mid \\psi, h) - w(x, \\alpha^*(\\psi, h)) + \\beta \\left[(1 - \\delta) J(\\psi, h, x) + \\delta V(h, x) \\right]\n    \\end{equation*}$$\n - **Workers:**\n\t  * *Value of unemployed worker:* $$\\begin{equation*}\n  U(h) = b + \\max_{x}\\left\\{ p(\\theta(h,x))\\int W(\\psi, h, x) dF(\\psi) + (1 - p(\\theta(h,x)))U(h)\\right\\}\n  \\end{equation*}$$\n\t* *Value of employed worker:*$$\\begin{equation*}\n  W(\\psi, h, x) = x + \\beta \\left[ (1 - \\delta) W(\\psi, h, x) + \\delta U(h) \\right]\n  \\end{equation*}$$",
      "type": "text",
      "width": 825,
      "x": -815,
      "y": 2400
    },
    {
      "height": 630,
      "id": "3adf148b601f6753",
      "styleAttributes": {
      },
      "text": "### Search \n\n- Type $h$ worker direct their search over promised utility values $x$. \n- Firms search for workers of type $h$ by promising utilities $x$.\n- Submarkets are indexed by $(h, x)$, tightness is defined as:$$\n  \\theta(h, x) = \\frac{v(h, x)}{u(h, x)}$$\n  - $v(h, x)$ = number of vacancies in submarket $w$\n  - $u(h, x)$ = number of unemployed people in submarket $w$\n  - Vacancy filling rate: $q(\\theta(h, x))$\n  - Job finding rate: $p(\\theta(h, x))$\n\n- There is free entry of firms with vacancy posting cost $\\kappa \\in \\mathbb{R}_{++}$.\n\t- $\\implies$ expected value of posting a vacancy is null.\n\n- Once a firm and a worked are matched the firm delivers $x$ utility to the worker following their optimal remote work policy.\n\n- The remote productivity of the firm is drawn from the exogenous distribution $F(\\psi)$. \n\t- Since firms are ex-ante homogenous the probability of being hired by a type $\\psi$ firm is the same in every submarket.\n- Matches are exogenously broken at a rate $\\delta$.",
      "type": "text",
      "width": 825,
      "x": -815,
      "y": 1320
    },
    {
      "height": 680,
      "id": "fe4bc5ae32071aa8",
      "styleAttributes": {
      },
      "text": "### Workers\n\n* Characterized by their productivity.  \n* Incur disutility from on-site work $(1-\\alpha)$, compensated by wage $(w)$.  \n  * $x(w,\\alpha)$: utility of a worker earning $w$ with remote work $\\alpha\\in[0,1]$ of the time.  \n    * $$x(w, \\alpha) = w - c (1 - \\alpha)^{\\chi}$$  \n    * $$c > 0$$ is, utility scaling factor and $$ \\chi > 1$$ is the curvature parameter.  \n    * *$x_{w}(w,\\alpha)>0$*  \n    * *$x_{\\alpha}(w,\\alpha)>0$*  \n* Labor market is segmented by worker type and promised utility: $(h,x)$.  \n  * $\\theta(h,x)$ is the sub-market tightness.  \n  * $p(\\theta(h,x))$ is the job finding rate.  \n* Choose where to apply based on maximizing expected utility.  ",
      "type": "text",
      "width": 735,
      "x": -815,
      "y": 360
    },
    {
      "height": 680,
      "id": "17868de185099e6c",
      "styleAttributes": {
      },
      "text": "### Firms\n\n* **Remote-work efficiency**: A firmâ€™s type $\\psi$ determines its efficiency in remote work.  \n* The output of a firm-worker match depends on the fraction of remote work ($\\alpha$) and the worker's skill ($h$):  \n  $$Y(\\alpha \\mid \\psi, h) = A(h)\\left((1 - \\alpha) + \\alpha g(h,\\psi)\\right)$$  \n  * $A'(h) > 0$: Higher-skilled workers ($h$) contribute more to productivity.  \n  * $g_{\\psi}(\\psi, h) \\geq 0$: Remote work efficiency increases with firm type ($\\psi$) due to better technology, better management practices or the nature of the occupation.  \n  * $g_{h}(\\psi, h) \\geq 0$: Remote work efficiency increases with skill ($h$) due to greater autonomy and technological ability.  \n* Firm is uncertain of $\\psi$ before posting. The distribution $F(\\psi)$ is known by all agents.  ",
